Headlines.Headline: W.W. Grainger Guidance for 2014 Falls Below Expectations

PARAGRAPH.#text: W.W. Grainger Inc. GWW on Wednesday issued earnings guidance for 2014 that fell below Wall Street expectations. The industrial goods supplier said it expects per-share earnings of $12.25 to $13 for next year. Analysts polled by Thomson Reuters were expecting $13.25 a share. For the current quarter, the company said it expects per-share earnings of $2.53 to $2.73, while analysts were expecting $2.65 a share. The company, sometimes considered a bellwether of the U.S. economy, has reported double-digit percentage profit growth recently, driven by increasing demand from businesses and institutions that are looking to consolidate suppliers.

At its annual analyst meeting in Lake Forest, Ill., Grainger forecast 2013 earnings of $10.85 to $12 a share on sales growth of 2% to 8%. Analysts polled by Thomson Reuters had projected per-share earnings of $12.01 and sales growth of 8%. Chairman and Chief Executive Jim Ryan said the company continues to see significant potential to gain share in the global maintenance, repair and operations market.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: Morning MarketBeat: Investors Prep for Bernanke
Headlines.Author: Steven Russolillo
Headlines.Headline: Morning MarketBeat: Investors Prep for Bernanke

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:MARKET SNAP: At 5:40 a.m. ET, S&P 500 futures down 0.2%. Treasurys higher. Nymex down 7 cents at $96.94; gold flat at $1,730.89. In Europe, FTSE 100 down 0.2%, DAX down 0.5% and CAC 40 down 0.8%. In Asia, Nikkei 225 up 0.4% and Hang Seng down 0.1%.Overnight action: Defense deal would roil industry; Assaults challenge U.S. Mideast policy; Economists uncertain about more Fed moves.Watch for: Weekly jobless claims (8:30 a.m. Eastern Time): Seen rising to 370,000 from 365,000 a week earlier. August producer price index (8:30): Seen rising 1.0% after expanding 0.3% a month earlier. EIA weekly natural gas storage report (10:30): natural gas in storage seen rising 26 Bcf, after rising 28 Bcf the week before. August federal budget (2:00)FOMC interest-rate decision (12:30 p.m.); Federal Reserve economic projections (2:00); Ben Bernanke press conference (2:15)For more MarketBeat and other streaming markets coverage from The Wall Street Journal, point your mobile browser to wsj.com/marketspulse.The Breakfast BriefingThe easy ride for stocks may get a bit more challenging.On tap later today is the conclusion of the Fed's two-day policy meeting and potential plans from the central bank to jumpstart the economy. If the Fed lets loose with more quantitative easing, the big question will be just how effective another shot of liquidity is for the economy, which is struggling with anemic growth and high unemployment.The consensus on Wall Street is calling for some form of additional Fed stimulus. An extension of the low-interest-rate policy into 2015 seems like a given. What's less clear is whether Chairman Ben Bernanke will unleash the big bazooka: QE3.Larry McDonald, senior director for credit, sales & trading at Newedge, compiled QE3 forecasts from seven big banks and found that Wall Street thinks there's a 60% chance QE3 will be unveiled.But whether QE3 is actually what the economy needs right now may be another story."This type of stimulus is designed to increase the supply of credit available to markets," Brad Thompson, chief investment officer of Watkinsville, Ga.-based Stadion Money Management, said in a chat with MarketBeat. "The problem is where is the demand? The public is still deleveraging and doesn’t desire more credit...I don’t know how effective more QE will be."For the most part, investors have coasted through many of the big events in September. From last week's jobs report, to the German Constitutional Court ruling and Apple's iPhone upgrade yesterday, stocks haven't had the big post-summer selloff many investors were anticipating.The Dow is up 1.9% in September (historically the worst month of the year for markets), while the euro has risen to a four-month high and European government bond yields have declined substantially.With the Dow already sitting at its highest level since December 2007, there are concerns that the potential for more Fed stimulus has already been priced into stocks."Equity markets would probably see a temporary lift from QE3, but I expect it to be fairly short lived," says Thompson of Stadion, which has about $5.3 billion in assets under management.If the Fed doesn’t unveil QE3, will investors be disappointed? Or will they quickly shrug off any disappointment and think another shot of stimulus may not be warranted now, but will come later?The thought process for investors is littered with question marks.What is clear is the smooth-sailing ride for stocks this month may be poised to get much bumpier.Morning MarketBeat Daily Factoid: On this day in 1996, Rapper Tupac died in Las Vegas six days after he was hurt in a drive-by shooting.-Steven RussolilloStocks to WatchApple shares were up marginally after hours Wednesday following the company’s unveiling of the iPhone 5.Pier 1 Imports is expected to report a profit of 19 cents a share on revenue of $368 million.W.W. Headlines.Author: Nathalie Tadena
Headlines.Headline: Grainger Raises Low End Of Year Guidance, Gives Upbeat 2012 Sales View

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES W.W. Grainger Inc. GWW raised the low end of its full-year guidance while it also issued a mostly upbeat forecast for 2012. The industrial-goods supplier now sees adjusted full-year earnings of $8.85 to $9 a share. In October, the company raised its estimate to $8.80 to $9 a share. Wednesday, Grainger forecast fourth-quarter earnings of $1.94 to $2.09 a share and sales growth of 12% to 13%. Analysts see earnings of $2.10 and 13% sales growth. It also said it will close 25 branches in the U.S.

reported a 12% rise in first-quarter and boosted its fiscal-year earnings forecast as the industrial-supplies company says it is gaining market share. The firm Monday posted net income of $114.2 million, or $1.43 a share, up from $101.8 million a year earlier. Revenue climbed 7.4% to $1.66 billion. The latest mean estimates of analysts polled by Thomson Financial were for earnings of $1.36 a share on $1.67 billion in revenue.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Grainger 1Q Net Up 12%; Boosts Earnings Forecast

Headlines.Author: Amanda Harris Falls

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES W.W. Grainger Inc.'s

first-quarter net earnings increased 12% to $114.2 million, or $1.43 a share, from $101.8 million, or $1.17 a share, a year ago, due in part to 6% growth in its branch-based business segment. Analysts surveyed by Thomson Financial expected, on average, earnings of $1.36 a share. The Chicago supplier of facilities maintenance products said net sales increased 7.4% to $1.66 billion from $1.55 billion the previous year.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Annuity sellers cry foul

#text:
Sellers of annuities are complaining about the president's budget
    proposal. The Clinton plan calls for making most exchanges between annuities taxable,
    including the reallocation of assets within a variable annuity, the Wall Street Journal
    reported Wednesday. The plan undermines two main selling points: tax deferral and the
    ability to reallocate money within an annuity. There are two types of annuities. Variable
    annuities operate very much like mutual funds with investors paying no tax on gains until
    money is withdrawn. Fixed annuities are backed by corporate and government bonds and
    deliver a guaranteed rate of return. "This is a huge mistake," says

, an executive vice president for the industry's largest seller of
    annuities,
. Critics of annuities, however welcome the move.
with the

in Fairfax, VA sees the proposal
    driving "a stake right through the heart" of the industry. Hopewell, who never
    recommends annuities, believes high fees and commissions on the products make them less
    attractive than mutual funds. Should the proposal become law, the case for owning
    annuities "will be even worse," he concluded.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Annuity sellers cry foul
